<subSubSection pageId="36" pageNumber="37" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="36.[151,1437,1525,1947]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
Karyotype: 2n = 54 and FN = 62. Autosomal complement: five medium to small metacentric and submetacentric pairs, and 21 acrocentric pairs (one large and the remaining medium to small decreasing in size). Sex chromosomes: X, a medium subtelocentric; Y, a small submetacentric (
<figureCitation box="[865,970,1633,1659]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="37.[151,250,1304,1328]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1256]" captionTargetId="figure-17@37.[151,1436,181,1263]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="FIGURE 10. Karyotype of Neacomys sp. 2, male with 2n = 54 and FN = 62. (A) Conventional staining (JAP 63); (B) C-banding (JAP 63); (C) G-banding (JAP 63); (D) Metaphase plate after fluorescent in situ hybridization with telomeric probe (left) and DAPI staining (right) (JAP 63)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4423639" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4423639/files/figure.png" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Fig. 10A</figureCitation>
). C-banding metaphases exhibited blocks of constitutive heterochromatin on the pericentromeric region of all autosomes. The X chromosome presented the short arm entirely heterochromatic. The Y chromosome presented the long arm entirely heterochromatic (
<figureCitation box="[1322,1423,1705,1731]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="37.[151,250,1304,1328]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1256]" captionTargetId="figure-17@37.[151,1436,181,1263]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="FIGURE 10. Karyotype of Neacomys sp. 2, male with 2n = 54 and FN = 62. (A) Conventional staining (JAP 63); (B) C-banding (JAP 63); (C) G-banding (JAP 63); (D) Metaphase plate after fluorescent in situ hybridization with telomeric probe (left) and DAPI staining (right) (JAP 63)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4423639" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4423639/files/figure.png" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Fig. 10B</figureCitation>
). G-banding was performed to allow the correct identification of all homologous pairs (
<figureCitation box="[1132,1236,1741,1767]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="37.[151,250,1304,1328]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1256]" captionTargetId="figure-17@37.[151,1436,181,1263]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="FIGURE 10. Karyotype of Neacomys sp. 2, male with 2n = 54 and FN = 62. (A) Conventional staining (JAP 63); (B) C-banding (JAP 63); (C) G-banding (JAP 63); (D) Metaphase plate after fluorescent in situ hybridization with telomeric probe (left) and DAPI staining (right) (JAP 63)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4423639" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4423639/files/figure.png" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Fig. 10C</figureCitation>
). FISH with telomeric sequences revealed signals exclusively at the ends of all chromosome arms and no interstitial signals were observed (
<figureCitation box="[266,370,1813,1839]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="37.[151,250,1304,1328]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1256]" captionTargetId="figure-17@37.[151,1436,181,1263]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="FIGURE 10. Karyotype of Neacomys sp. 2, male with 2n = 54 and FN = 62. (A) Conventional staining (JAP 63); (B) C-banding (JAP 63); (C) G-banding (JAP 63); (D) Metaphase plate after fluorescent in situ hybridization with telomeric probe (left) and DAPI staining (right) (JAP 63)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4423639" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4423639/files/figure.png" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Fig. 10D</figureCitation>
). The same diploid number (2n=54) and a similar fundamental number (FN=66) was reported by 
<bibRefCitation author="Silva, W. O. &amp; Pieczarka, J. C. &amp; Ferguson-Smith, M. A. &amp; O'Brien, P. C. M. &amp; Mendes-Oliveira, A. C. &amp; Sampaio, I. &amp; Carneiro, J. &amp; Nagamachi, C. Y." box="[151,354,1849,1875]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" pagination="0182218" refId="ref73755" refString="Silva, W. O., Pieczarka, J. C., Ferguson-Smith, M. A., O'Brien, P. C. M., Mendes-Oliveira, A. C., Sampaio, I., Carneiro, J. &amp; Nagamachi, C. Y. (2017) Chromosomal diversity and molecular divergence among three undescribed species of Neacomys (Rodentia, Sigmodontinae) separated by Amazonian rivers. Public Library of Science one, 12 (8), e 0182218. https: // doi. org / 10.1371 / journal. pone. 0182218" type="journal article" year="2017">
Silva 
<emphasis box="[216,265,1849,1875]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">et al</emphasis>
. (2017)
</bibRefCitation>
for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1900" box="[400,515,1850,1875]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Neacomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[400,515,1850,1875]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Neacomys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. B. However, the former karyotype presented five large and two small biarmed pairs, different from the karyotype presented by us that comprises five medium to small biarmed pairs. The sex chromosomes morphology was also distinctly between the two karyotypes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
